ents of the route data area must be zero.        When an internet module routes a datagram it checks to see if        the record route option is present.  If it is, it inserts its        own internet address as known in the environment into which this        datagram is being forwarded into the recorded route begining at        the octet indicated by the pointer, and increments the pointer        by four.        If the route data area is already full (the pointer exceeds the        length) the datagram is forwarded without inserting the address        into the recorded route.  If there is some room but not enough        room for a full address to be inserted, the original datagram is        considered to be in error and is discarded.  In either case an        ICMP parameter problem message may be sent to the source        host [3].        Not copied on fragmentation, goes in first fragment only.        Appears at most once in a datagram.      Stream Identifier        +--------+--------+--------+--------+        |10001000|00000010|    Stream ID    |        +--------+--------+--------+--------+         Type=136 Length=4        This option provides a way for the 16-bit SATNET stream        identifier to be carried through networks that do not support        the stream concept.        Must be copied on fragmentation.  Appears at most once in a        datagram.                                                               [Page 21]                                                          September 1981Internet ProtocolSpecification      Internet Timestamp        +--------+--------+--------+--------+        |01000100| length | pointer|oflw|flg|        +--------+--------+--------+--------+        |         internet address          |        +--------+--------+--------+--------+        |             timestamp             |        +--------+--------+--------+--------+        |                 .                 |              